                <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-600 mb-10 italic border-l-4 border-medicalTeal pl-6">
                    <strong>PRP stands for Platelet-Rich Plasma</strong> — it is a medical treatment in which a concentrated solution of platelets is extracted from your own blood and injected into a targeted area of the body to promote natural healing and tissue regeneration. PRP is widely used for <a href="../hair-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">hair regrowth</a>, skin rejuvenation, facial aesthetics, and joint pain relief. Because it uses your body's own biological material, it is considered one of the safest regenerative therapies available today.
                </p>

                <p>If you have been searching for answers about PRP treatment — what it is, how it works, whether it is right for you, and what kind of results you can expect — you are in the right place. In this complete beginner guide, we will explain everything about <strong>Platelet-Rich Plasma therapy</strong> in simple language, so you can make an informed decision about your health and appearance.</p>

                <p>At <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">DenceSpot Clinic in Gurgaon</a>, we perform PRP therapy for hair loss, facial rejuvenation, and other aesthetic concerns every week. We have seen firsthand how this treatment transforms lives — from restoring thinning hair to giving patients a renewed sense of confidence. Let us walk you through everything you need to know.</p>

                <h2>What Does PRP Stand For? Understanding the Full Form</h2>

                <p><strong>PRP full form is Platelet-Rich Plasma.</strong> To understand what this means, let us break it down into its components:</p>

                <p><strong>Platelets</strong> are a type of blood cell that plays a critical role in wound healing and tissue repair. They are the first responders when your body suffers an injury. Platelets rush to the site, form a clot to stop bleeding, and then release growth factors — specialized proteins that signal surrounding cells to start repairing and regenerating tissue.</p>

                <p><strong>Plasma</strong> is the liquid component of your blood. It is a pale yellow fluid that makes up about 55 percent of your total blood volume. Plasma carries red blood cells, white blood cells, platelets, nutrients, hormones, and proteins throughout your body.</p>

                <p><strong>Platelet-Rich Plasma</strong>, therefore, is a portion of your plasma that has been processed to contain a significantly higher concentration of platelets than normal blood — typically 3 to 5 times higher. This concentrated solution is packed with growth factors such as Platelet-Derived Growth Factor (PDGF), Transforming Growth Factor (TGF), Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor (VEGF), and Epidermal Growth Factor (EGF). These growth factors are the reason PRP is so effective at stimulating healing and regeneration.</p>

                <h2>How Does PRP Treatment Work? The Science Behind It</h2>

                <p>The science behind PRP is grounded in your body's natural healing mechanism. When you cut your finger or scrape your knee, your body sends platelets to the injured area. These platelets release growth factors that trigger a cascade of healing events — new blood vessel formation, collagen production, cell multiplication, and tissue repair.</p>

                <p>PRP therapy harnesses this same biological process, but in a targeted and amplified way. By concentrating your platelets and injecting them directly into a specific area — such as a thinning scalp, aging skin, or an injured joint — the treatment delivers a powerful dose of growth factors exactly where they are needed most.</p>

                <p>For hair loss specifically, PRP works by stimulating dormant or weakened hair follicles. The growth factors increase blood supply to the follicle, extend the growth phase (anagen phase) of the hair cycle, and promote the production of thicker, healthier hair strands. Multiple clinical studies published in dermatology journals have confirmed that PRP can increase hair count, hair thickness, and the overall strength of hair roots. You can learn more about this in our <a href="prp-hair-treatment-natural-way-to-regrow-hair.php">detailed PRP for hair regrowth guide</a>.</p>

                <h2>The PRP Procedure: Step-by-Step Process</h2>

                <p>One of the biggest advantages of PRP therapy is that the procedure is straightforward, minimally invasive, and can be completed within 45 to 60 minutes. Here is exactly what happens during a PRP session at a clinic:</p>

                <h3>Step 1: Blood Collection</h3>
                <p>A small amount of blood — usually 10 to 20 millilitres, similar to a routine blood test — is drawn from a vein in your arm. This is the same process as any standard blood draw, and it takes only a couple of minutes.</p>

                <h3>Step 2: Centrifugation (Processing)</h3>
                <p>The collected blood is placed into a specialized centrifuge machine that spins at high speed. This spinning separates the blood into three layers: red blood cells at the bottom, platelet-poor plasma at the top, and a thin golden layer of Platelet-Rich Plasma in the middle. This PRP layer is carefully extracted using a syringe.</p>

                <h3>Step 3: Preparation of the Treatment Area</h3>
                <p>The treatment area — whether it is your scalp, face, or another body part — is cleaned and numbed using a topical anaesthetic cream or local anaesthesia. This ensures minimal discomfort during the injection process.</p>

                <h3>Step 4: PRP Injection</h3>
                <p>The concentrated PRP is then injected into the targeted area using fine needles. For hair treatment, the injections are made directly into the scalp at the level of the hair follicles, focusing on areas of thinning or hair loss. For facial treatments, the PRP is injected into specific areas of the face or applied after microneedling.</p>

                <h3>Step 5: Post-Treatment Care</h3>
                <p>After the procedure, you can return to your normal activities almost immediately. There is no downtime. Your doctor will provide specific aftercare instructions, such as avoiding washing your hair for 24 hours (for scalp PRP) or avoiding direct sun exposure (for facial PRP).</p>

                <h2>Uses of PRP Treatment — Where Is It Applied?</h2>

                <p>PRP therapy is remarkably versatile. While it gained mainstream popularity for hair loss treatment, its applications extend across multiple medical and aesthetic fields:</p>

                <h3>PRP for Hair Loss and Hair Regrowth</h3>
                <p>This is the most popular use of PRP in India. <a href="../hair-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">PRP for hair</a> is effective for both men and women experiencing Androgenetic Alopecia (pattern baldness), Telogen Effluvium (stress-related hair fall), and general hair thinning. It strengthens existing hair, reactivates dormant follicles, and is also used as a complementary treatment after a <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">hair transplant</a> to improve graft survival and accelerate healing. If you are struggling with hair fall, our <a href="how-to-control-hair-fall-complete-guide.php">complete hair fall control guide</a> covers all your options in detail.</p>

                <h3>PRP for Face and Skin Rejuvenation (Vampire Facial)</h3>
                <p>PRP facial treatment, often called the "Vampire Facial," involves applying PRP to the face after a microneedling session. The growth factors penetrate deep into the skin, boosting collagen and elastin production. This helps reduce fine lines, wrinkles, acne scars, enlarged pores, and uneven skin tone. The result is smoother, firmer, and more youthful-looking skin.</p>

                <h3>PRP for Under-Eye Dark Circles</h3>
                <p>The delicate skin under the eyes is one of the first areas to show signs of aging and fatigue. PRP injections in this area help improve skin thickness, reduce pigmentation, and diminish the hollow appearance that causes dark circles.</p>

                <h3>PRP for Joint Pain and Sports Injuries</h3>
                <p>Orthopaedic surgeons and sports medicine specialists use PRP to treat conditions such as knee osteoarthritis, tennis elbow, rotator cuff injuries, ligament sprains, and Achilles tendon problems. The growth factors accelerate tissue repair and reduce inflammation, offering pain relief and improved function.</p>

                <h3>PRP for Wound Healing</h3>
                <p>In surgical and post-surgical settings, PRP is used to speed up the healing of chronic wounds, surgical incisions, and skin grafts. It is particularly useful for patients with diabetes or other conditions that impair normal wound healing.</p>

